# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1889-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Brooklyn baseball club was formed in 1883 by real estate magnate and baseball enthusiast Charles Byrne who convinced his brother-in-law Joseph Doyle and casino operator Ferdinand Abell to start the team with him.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Byrne set up a grandstand on fifth avenue and named it Washington Park in honor of George Washington.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The team played in the minor Inter-State Association of Professional Baseball Clubs.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Doyle became the first manager of the team, which drew 6,000 fans to its first home game on May 12, 1883, against the Trenton team.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] (This was actually the second game the club played in Brooklyn; three days earlier, with Washington Park not yet ready, the Greys beat Harrisburg 7–1 at the Parade Ground.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] It was the only professional match ever held at the ground, with some 2,000 fans in attendance.) The team won the league title after the **Camden Merritt** club disbanded on July 20 and Brooklyn picked up some of its better players.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Grays were invited to join the American Association for the following season.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1889-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **1884 Brooklyn Atlantics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] It was the first season in the American Association for the team, and they finished the year in ninth place.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn baseball team had played as the **Brooklyn Grays** in the Interstate Association in 1883, where they won the championship.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] In 1884, Charles Byrne moved the team into the American Association, renaming them the Atlantics in tribute to the old National Association Brooklyn Atlantics team.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The **1884 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1884.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American Association's regular seasons ended on October 15, with the Providence Grays and New York Metropolitans as the NL and AA pennant winners, respectively.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The newly founded Union Association regular season ended on October 19, with the St.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the first World's Championship Series (the first inter-league championship game of its kind in the Major Leagues) on October 23 and ended with Game 3 on October 25, in what was a best-of-five-playoff.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Grays swept the Metropolitans in three games, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1884 season, in September 1883, the Union Association was formed, in direct contravention to the reserve rule (that a ballplayer could be reserved by a team) of the 1883 National Agreement (a.k.a.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Tripartite Agreement) signed between the National League, American Association, and minor league Northwestern League.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] In response to formation of the UA, the AA expanded their league from an eight teams to twelve teams to undermine the weak footing the UA had, as UA teams were mostly in cities that already had established AA and NL teams.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The latter played their last game on August 2, and were replaced by the minor league Eastern League's Richmond Virginians to finish Washington's schedule.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association was largely unstable throughout its only year in existence (though confidence in the league remained high), as three of its founding teams would not make it to the end of the season.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Altoona Mountain Citys folded on May 31, and were replaced by the Kansas City Cowboys on June 7.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Keystones folded on August 7, and were replaced by the Eastern League's Wilmington Quicksteps.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Browns relocated to Pittsburgh as the Pittsburgh Stogies following their August 21 game.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Quicksteps would fold on September 15, while the Stogies would fold just three days later.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] On September 27, the Milwaukee Brewers and St.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Paul Saints) were recruited from the Northwestern League to finish the Philadelphia / Wilmington and Chicago/Pittsburgh schedules, respectively.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 season featured the second African American player in the major leagues (following William Edward White five years prior), debuting May 1 and playing 42 games for the Toledo Blue Stockings of the American Association.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] During his tenure, he faced abuse from other players (including teammates), fans, and the press, and even threats of being mobbed by 75 men before a road trip to Richmond, Virginia, before being released due to injury on September 29, prior to the road trip.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] His brother Weldy Walker played on the Toledo Blue Stockings for five games between July and August, becoming the third African American in the major leagues.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 schedule consisted of 110 games for all teams in the American Association, which had twelve active teams, and 112 games for all teams in the National League and Union Association, each of which had eight active teams.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 10 games against the other eleven teams in their league, and each of NL & UA teams were scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League increased its total games per team from 98 to 112, 14 games to 16 games per seven opponents.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The new Union Association copied this format.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the American Association, expanding from eight to twelve teams, changed from the 98-game format to the 110-game format.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would continue to use their 112-game format through the following season, while the American Association would copy the NL format.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Union Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while American Association and National League Opening Days took place on May 1, featuring all twelve and all eight teams, respectively.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 19 featuring four teams, while the American Association and National League would see their final day of the regular season on October 15 featuring all twelve teams and four teams, respectively.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 World's Championship Series took place between October 23 and October 25.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four teams played in four neutral or alternate sites in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] 35 tie games (19 in AA, 10 in NL, 6 in UA), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four of these teams folded, one of which relocated cities prior to folding.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers hosted 11 Sunday games at the Bruce Grounds north of Indianapolis city limits in Center Township on May 18, 25, June 22, 29, July 6, 13, 20, August 3, 10, 31, and September 21.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1889-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1889-world-series/1885-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1885 Brooklyn Grays** finished the season in fifth place.
[src:1889-world-series/1885-brooklyn-grays-season] The team added several players from the defunct Cleveland Blues team after team owner Charlie Byrne bought the Blues assets for $10,000 after the 1884 season.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] The **1889 World Series** was an end-of-the-year baseball playoff series between the National League champion New York Giants and the American Association champion Brooklyn Bridegrooms (later known as the Dodgers).
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] This Series was part of the pre-modern-era World Series, an annual competition between the champions of the National League and the American Association.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] The Giants won this best-of-11-games series, 6 games to 3.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] The 1889 Series was the first involving solely New York City area clubs, and was part of the continuum of a long-standing rivalry that developed between the clubs in New York, particularly the Giants and the Dodgers.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] Brooklyn was then a separate city from New York; Brooklyn (and the other three boroughs) would merge with New York City in 1898.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] Despite this Series setback, the Brooklyn team would come back strong in 1890.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] The club transferred to the National League, and with the Giants suffering raids by the Players' League, would win the league championship; it was the first major league club to win consecutive pennants in two different leagues.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] The New York Giants defeated the Brooklyn Bridegrooms in the 1889 World Series, 6 games to 3.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] On October 17, the two clubs owners, John B.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] Byrne of the Brooklyn club, met to arrange a post-season series.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] They agreed that the Series would end when one club had won six games.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] The Series commenced the next day, and continued through October 29, when the Giants won their sixth game, ending the Series.
[src:1889-world-series/1889-world-series] Attendance was good for the first two games, at the Polo Grounds and Washington Park, respectively, but the weather turned cold and rainy, and the remainder of the Series was sparsely attended.
